# Yardly API Security Rules (v1.0)

## Tenant Context (mandatory)
- For tenant-scoped endpoints, use centralized tenant extraction via guard + decorator (`CurrentTenantGuard` + `@CurrentTenant()`).
- Do not scatter ad-hoc `tenantId` reads across controller/service code paths.
- If tenant id is present in multiple places (header/param/body), reject mismatches (`tenant_id_mismatch`) and proceed only with one validated value.

## Tenant and ID Validation
- Current primary identifiers in this codebase are Prisma `cuid()` strings (not UUID).
- Do not enforce UUID pipes/validators for `tenantId` / `membershipId` unless Prisma schema changes.
- Validate tenant-scoped params/body early in controller/guard to fail fast on invalid ids.

## Auth Guard Hardening
- Return generic `Unauthorized` to clients; never expose internal configuration state in auth error messages.
- Avoid expensive remote auth verification on every request when a safe short cache can reduce repeated lookups.
- Keep sensitive auth details in internal logs only.

## API Abuse Protection
- Keep global API rate limiting enabled.
- Apply stricter limits for abuse-prone routes (`/auth/me`, invitations, and similar endpoints).

## CORS and Response Exposure
- Use strict origin allowlist matching sourced from `ADMIN_ORIGIN`.
- Avoid broad wildcard behavior with credentialed requests.
- Keep public health/error responses minimal; do not expose infrastructure internals to end users.

## Logging and UI-Facing Errors
- Use centralized structured JSON logging in API (`JsonLoggerService`) with stable keys (timestamp, level, context, message).
- Ensure request logging includes `x-request-id` (generate if missing) and return it in response headers for traceability.
- Do not log raw PII or full upstream provider messages when avoidable.
- Admin UI should not display raw backend/provider error text, stack traces, env keys, or internal URLs.
- User-facing messages must remain generic, concise, and in Ukrainian.
